NOTE 24/06/26

From https://arxiv.org/html/2604.03857v1

An essential design question is determining when to invoke the LLM to adjust
CWND. This requires a trigger module that continuously monitors network
conditions and decides whether an adjustment should be applied. In conventional
loss-based congestion control algorithms such as TCP-NewReno, congestion is
detected through packet loss signals. However, these signals are inherently
delayed, as the receipt of 3-duplicate ACKs indicates that congestion has
already occurred. To enable earlier intervention, we adopt a latency-based
approach inspired by existing delay-sensitive congestion control schemes (e.g.,
Bbr [6]), which treat RTT growth as an early indicator of congestion rather
than waiting for loss. Specifically, we monitor the latency of the most
recently sent segment, and if it exceeds a predefined threshold, we trigger the
LLM to adjust CWND.




| Field                       | Simple meaning                                                         |
| --------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `tcpi_rcv_ssthresh`         | Receive-side slow-start threshold; a receive-window/auto-tuning limit. |
| `tcpi_rtt`                  | Smoothed round-trip time estimate, in microseconds.                    |
| `tcpi_rttvar`               | RTT variation / jitter estimate.                                       |
| `tcpi_snd_ssthresh`         | Send-side slow-start threshold.                                        |
| `tcpi_snd_cwnd`             | Current send congestion window (`cwnd`).                               |
| `tcpi_rcv_rtt`              | Receive-side RTT estimate used by the kernel.                          |
| `tcpi_total_retrans`        | Total retransmissions on this connection.                              |
| `tcpi_bytes_acked`          | Total application bytes acknowledged by the peer.                      |
| `tcpi_bytes_received`       | Total application bytes received from the peer.                        |
| `tcpi_segs_out`             | Total TCP segments sent.                                               |
| `tcpi_segs_in`              | Total TCP segments received.                                           |
| `tcpi_data_segs_in`         | Data segments received (not just control packets).                     |
| `tcpi_data_segs_out`        | Data segments sent (not just control packets).                         |
| `tcpi_delivery_rate`        | Estimated delivery throughput, bytes/sec.                              |
| `tcpi_delivered`            | Number of packets/segments delivered to the peer as tracked by TCP.    |
| `tcpi_bytes_sent`           | Total bytes sent, including retransmissions.                           |
| `tcpi_bytes_retrans`        | Total bytes retransmitted.                                             |


